# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tencent-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] In the video game industry, a **live service game** (also referred to as **games as a service**, abbreviated to **GaaS**) represents providing video games or game content on a continuing revenue model, similar to software as a service.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Live service games are ways to monetize video games either after their initial sale, or to support a free-to-play model.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Games released under the live service model are designed to receive a long or indefinite stream of monetized new content over time to encourage players to continue paying to support the game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] This often leads to games that work under a live service model to be called "**living games**" or "**live games**" since they continually change with these updates.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] The idea of games as a service began with the introduction of massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) like *RuneScape* and *World of Warcraft*, where the game's subscription model approach assured continued revenues to the developer and publisher to create new content.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Over time, new forms of offering continued GaaS revenues have come about.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] A significant impact on the use of GaaS was the expansion of mobile gaming, which often includes a social element, such as playing or competing with friends, and with players wanting to buy into GaaS to continue to play with friends.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Another influential game establishing games as a service was *Team Fortress 2*.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] To fight against a shrinking player-base, Valve released the first of several free updates in 2008, the "Gold Rush Update" which featured new weapons and cosmetic skins that could be unlocked through in-game achievements.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Further updates added similar weapons which began to include monetization options, such as buying virtual keys to open in-game loot boxes.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Valve began earning enough from these revenues to transition *Team Fortress 2* to a free-to-play title.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Valve carried this principle over to *Counter-Strike: Global Offensive* and to *Dota 2*, the latter of which was in competition with *League of Legends* by Riot Games.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] To remain competitive, *League of Legends*, which already had a microtransaction model in place, began adding new game content regularly, such as a new playable character every few weeks for several years straight.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] This contributed to the creation of the concept of lifestyle games such as *Destiny* and *Tom Clancy's The Division*.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Revenue from these subscriptions pay for the computer servers used to run the game, the people that manage and oversee the game on a daily basis, and the introduction of new content into the game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] cap, after which they are required to pay to continue to play.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] grant subscribers complete access to a large library of games offered digitally with no limitations.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Users need to download these games to their local computer or console to play.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] that requires an active account to play.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] New games are typically added to the service, and in some cases, games may leave the service, after which subscribers will be unable to play that title.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Such services may offer the ability to purchase these titles to own and allow them to play outside of the subscription service.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] on local devices, eliminating the need for specialized console hardware or powerful personal computers, outside of the necessary bandwidth for Internet connectivity.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] These otherwise operate similar to game services, in that the library of available titles may be added to or removed from over time, depending on the service.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] , that provide some form of additional content to the purchaser.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] that provide a random assortment of items and rewards.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Players do not necessarily need to purchase these items with real-world funds to acquire them.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] These select "whales" providing sufficient revenue to support further development of new content.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Games with season passes provide one or more large content updates over the course of about a year, or a "season" in these terms.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] which provides new customization options that a player can earn by completing challenges in a game, but only if they have bought into the battle pass; content on a battle pass is typically only obtainable during a limited time.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] In contrast to microtransactions in which players can buy but not usually capable of trading items with other players, blockchain games encourage players to create value with blockchain items and trade and sell these, with the developer or publisher taking a small fee on each transaction.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] As of 2021, blockchain games have yet to catch on due to the stigmas associated with cryptocurrency and NFTs.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Games may combine one or more of these forms.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] A common example are lifestyle games, which provide rotating daily content, which frequently reward the player with in-game currency to buy new equipment (otherwise purchasable with real-world funds), and extended by updates to the overall game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Examples of such lifestyle games include *Destiny*, *Destiny 2* and many MMORPGs like *World of Warcraft*.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] The principal reason that many developers and publishers have adopted GaaS is financial, giving them the ability to capture more revenue from the market than with a single release title (otherwise known as "games as a product").
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] While not all players will be willing to spend additional money to gain new content, there can be enough demand from a smaller population of players to support the service model.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] For example, for *World of Warcraft*, it was estimated on the basis of average revenue per user (ARPU), that only 5% of the game's population paid 20 times more than the baseline ARPU, sufficient to continue ongoing development of the game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] GaaS further represents a means by which games can improve their reputation to critics and players by continued improvements over time, using revenues earned from GaaS monetization to support the continued development and to draw in new sales for the product.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Titles like *Diablo III* and *Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege* are examples of games offering GaaS which initially launched with lukewarm reception but have been improved with continued service improvements.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Games as a service also impacts the development process for games.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] When developing a game as a product, there is generally a linear flow of tasks to assure that the product shipped is free of software bugs and other problems that may exist, which can be both time-consuming and costly to test for.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] If there are critical bugs found post-release, this can also be costly to develop, test and distribute software updates to rectify.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Further, games developed as a service are more commonly driven by player feedback, so initial iterations of a game's release may be lightweight to be used as a foundation to build upon based on the game's community.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] This can further shorten the initial development cycle of a game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] However, games as a service also increased overall development effort as there are usually two or more concurrent tracks to support a game; one working to support the current available release, and others that are working on the future content that will be added to the game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] While the games as a service model is aimed to extend revenues, the model also aimed to eliminate legal issues related to software licenses, specifically the concept of software ownership versus license.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Case law for video games remains unclear whether retail and physical game products qualify as goods or services.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] If treated as goods, the purchaser gains several rights, in particular those related to the first-sale doctrine, which allows them to resell or trade these games, and which can subsequently affect sales revenue to publishers.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] The industry has generally considered that physical games are a service, enforced through end-user license agreements (EULAs) to try to limit post-sale activities, but these have generally not been enforceable since they affect consumers' rights, leading to confusion in the area.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Instead, by transitioning to games as a service, where there is a clear service being offered, publishers and developers can clearly establish their works as services rather than goods.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] This further gives publishers more control over the use of the software and what actions users can do through an enforceable EULA, such as preventing class action lawsuits.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Certain games can also be hosted in a cloud server, eliminating the need for installation in players' computers and consoles.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] In 2017, industry analysis firm Digital River estimated that by 2016, 25% of the revenue of games on personal computers resulted from one form or another of GaaS.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] The firm argued that this reflected on consumers that wanted more out of games that were otherwise offered at full price (US$60 at the time of the report) or looking for discounts, thus making the market ripe for post-release monetization.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] GaaS is also seen as a developing avenue for indie video games, which frequently have a wider potential install base (across computer, consoles, and mobile devices) that they can draw service revenues from.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Electronic Arts had earned $2 billion from GaaS transactions in 2018.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] The COVID-19 pandemic, which forced much of the world to stay at home to prevent its spread, was a further boom to the video game industry overall, including a major push for live service games, expanding their staff and capabilities to match.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] This led to an over saturation of the market by 2020.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Developing for live service games can change the culture of video game development, since rather than developing towards a single release and moving on to the next game, developers have to plan for continued content beyond release as well as ongoing support for the game.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Due to this cost, live service games ultimately are shuttered by their developers and publishers for various reasons, such as waning player interest, shifting costs on the business, or moving away from aging technology.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] However, in the 2020s, the question of the sustainability of live service games was raised as many live-service games were terminated well ahead of anticipated lifecycles.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] An early example of such a game was *Anthem*, released in 2019, which failed to meet sales expectations, and while long-term plans were made to improve the game, its development was ultimately cancelled by 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Epic Games, the developers behind *Fortnite*, announced large cuts of around 900 and 1,000 in 2023 and 2026, respectively, the latter layoffs partially a result of waning engagement with *Fortnite*.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] These cuts also led to discontinuation of some of the game modes within *Fortnite* with Epic seeking to improve the remaining experiences for players.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Commentators saw this as a signal that live service games may not be as sustainable as once thought.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] As more games switched towards live services, competition for players grew, making the prospect of live service games a risky one.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Similarly, hero shooter *Highguard* was developed by Wildlight which was made up of several former Respawn Entertainment developers that had worked on *Apex Legends*, with the game developed to try to capture some of the facets that had made *Apex* a success.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Existing live service games can also be impacted by new competitors, with Bungie announcing it would end live service updates for *Destiny 2* in June 2026, though will keep the game playable indefinitely.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Stella Chung, writing for *IGN* and using *MultiVersus*, published by Warner Bros.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] Games, as an example, criticized the lack of access when live service games go offline, especially for those who invest money in it.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] She also pointed out the oversaturation of the market with free-to-play live service games, and that many live service games struggle, leading to them shutting down.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] On January 31, 2025, it was announced that *MultiVersus* would be delisted and its online servers closed permanently on March 30, 2025, after the end of the fifth and final season, remaining playable in offline modes.
[src:tencent-cloud/gaming-as-a-service] While one petition from this initiative reached the UK government by February 2025, the government opted to not take steps to modify laws for such cases but saying that game publishers were still bound by other consumer protection laws.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Livestreaming services encompass a wide variety of topics, including social media, video games, professional sports, and lifecasting.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Platforms such as Facebook Live, Periscope, Kuaishou, Douyu, bilibili, YouTube, and 17 include the streaming of scheduled promotions and celebrity events as well as streaming between users, as in videotelephony.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Livestreaming sites such as Twitch and Kick have become popular outlets for watching people play video games, such as in esports, Let's Play-style gaming, or speedrunning.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Live coverage of sporting events is a common application.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Chat rooms are a key feature in livestreaming, allowing viewers to interact with the broadcaster (streamer) and join ongoing conversations.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] These rooms often include emojis and emotes as additional communication tools.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In the field of social media, the term *live media* refers to new media that use streaming technologies to create and share live multimedia content among people, companies, and organizations.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Social media marketer Bryan Kramer describes livestreaming as an inexpensive "key marketing and communications tool that helps brands reach their online audience." Users can follow their friends' live video "shares" as well as "shares" related to specific content or items.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Live media can be shared through any Internet website or application; thus, when people browse a specific website, they may find live media streams relevant to them.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Live media can include coverage of various events such as concerts or live news coverage viewed using a web browser or apps such as Snapchat.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] James Harden and Trolli promoted an upcoming NBA All-Star Game through Snapchat.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Many of LaBeouf, Rönkkö & Turner's performance art were livestreamed, such as a stream of Shia LaBeouf in a theater viewing all his movies.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] However, live stream commerce today enables sellers to showcase products through streamers, mimicking in-store sales tactics to encourage customer purchases.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Chinese live stream-based retailing has contributed significantly to the country’s e-commerce sector, with reports estimating revenues in the tens of billions of pounds.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The McKinsey report also demonstrates that live stream commerce is expanding in China, the sales from live stream commerce were expected to achieve $423 billion by 2022,.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] It is expected the US live streaming industry will grow from $17 billion in 2022 to $55 billion by 2026.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Facebook introduced a video streaming service, Facebook Watch to select individuals in August 2017, and to the public in January 2018.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Facebook watch is a video-on-demand service that allows users to share content live.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] It allows people to upload videos that cover a wide array of topics including original comedy, drama, and news programming.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Facebook Live allows Facebook users to include their own "reactions" when someone is broadcasting.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] One of the reasons that Facebook Watch is so successful is because the content is recommended to users based on algorithms that determine what the user would most like to watch.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] YouTube was purchased by Google in 2006, and the pair subsequently announced their livestreaming app.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Like Periscope, users can comment during the broadcast.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Unlike Periscope, livestreams on YouTube can be saved and any user can access them through the app.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Kick (also known as Kick.com) is a live video streaming service supported by online betting Stake.com along with streaming personality Trainwreckstv.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Launched in 2022 as an Amazon-owned Twitch alternative, Kick emerged after Stake.com and other gambling sites were restricted on Twitch.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Kick offers a 95% revenue share to streamers and 5% to the platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Although Kick is not officially linked to Stake.com co-founders, records show they are the main shareholders of the company owning the streaming site.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Notable streamers like Hikaru Nakamura and Nickmercs, formerly popular on Twitch, joined Kick, contributing to its average of 235,000 live streams per day as of June 2023.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Lifestreaming, also known as lifecasting, is the practice of continuously broadcasting various aspects of one's daily life to an online audience.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] This modern phenomenon allows people to share even mundane events in real-time, giving viewers an intimate look into someone's routine.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Justin Kan, an entrepreneur and internet personality, is often credited with bringing this concept to the mainstream.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] He founded Justin.tv, a website initially focused solely on broadcasting his own life 24/7.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] This lifecasting platform eventually evolved, serving as the foundation for a new style of online sharing and paving the way for more diverse content.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In its early days, Justin.tv was an experimental space where Kan himself was the main focus, capturing everything from his workdays to social interactions.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] This format marked an early example of real-time personal broadcasting using emerging internet technologies.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Kan's innovation in this area led to the popularization of lifestreaming, which has since evolved to include various forms of content and millions of users worldwide.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Today, the influence of the original concept can be seen across multiple platforms and in different variations, extending beyond individual lifecasting to live broadcasts of events, gaming, and more.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Twitch is a livestreaming video platform owned by Twitch Interactive, a subsidiary of Amazon.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Introduced in June 2011 as a spin-off of the general-interest streaming platform, Justin.tv, the site primarily focuses on video game livestreaming, including broadcasts of eSports competitions, in addition to music broadcasts, creative content, and more recently, "in real life" streams.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Content on the site can be viewed either live or via video on demand.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Bigo Live is a live streaming platform owned by a Singapore-based BIGO Technology, which was founded in 2014 by David Li and Jason Hu.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] As of 2019, BIGO Technology is owned by JOYY, a Chinese company listed on the NASDAQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Like YouTube Live, users can watch trendy live streams and comment on the broadcast.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Unlike YouTube Live, users on Bigo Live can filter out broadcasters from a certain country on the explore page.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In March 2015, Twitter launched a livestreaming app called Periscope.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Normally, users would see a hyperlink attached to their broadcast, directing people to a new tab.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Using Periscope, videos appear live on the timeline.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] If the user has allowed the site to share information, others can see where the user is streaming from.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] During the broadcast, users can comment, talk to the broadcaster, or ask questions.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Kayvon Beykpour, CEO of Periscope, and Dick Costolo and Jack Dorsey, former CEOs of Twitter, all shared a common goal—to invent something that would merge both teams into one instead of as partners.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] It was discontinued in March 2021 due to declining usage, product realignment and high maintenance costs.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Microsoft entered the livestreaming scene when it acquired Beam, the Seattle-based company, in August 2016.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] About a year after acquiring the company, the service was renamed to Mixer in May 2017.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The platform was the first to bring multiple features to livestreaming such as interactive gameplay, where viewers could influence gameplay, and co-streaming, where viewers could watch multiple viewpoints of teammates in the same game.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Like Twitch, viewers on Mixer could pay to subscribe to streamers on a monthly basis.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Viewers could also buy "Embers", which was the e-currency used by the site, and could donate that to streamers as well.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] While Twitch remained the biggest company in the business, Mixer attempted to raise its stock by signing multiple big streamers to Mixer-exclusive deals.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] These signings included Tyler "Ninja" Blevins in August 2019, Michael "Shroud" Grzesiek in October 2019, and Cory "King Gothalion" Michael also in October 2019.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Mixer announced it would be shutting down its streaming services on July 22, 2020.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In the announcement, Mixer's parent company, Microsoft, announced a partnership with Facebook gaming, and directed current users to the new platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Livestreaming playing of video games gained popularity during the 2010s.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Ewalt referred to Twitch as "the ESPN of video games".
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The website spawned from and grew to overshadow Justin.tv, and was purchased by Amazon.com at the end of 2014 for US$970 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] As one of the leading livestreaming platforms, Twitch now has millions of broadcasters and has nearly two hundred million viewers.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Other video-game oriented streaming websites include Smashcast.tv, which was formed after the merging of Azubu and Hitbox.tv, and the South Korea-based afreecaTV.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In 2015, YouTube launched YouTube Gaming—a video gaming-oriented sub-site and app that is intended to compete with Twitch.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] An example of a notable livestreamed event is Games Done Quick, a charity speedrunning marathon hosted on Twitch.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Viewers are encouraged to donate for incentives during the stream such as naming characters in a run, having the runners attempt more difficult challenges, or winning prizes.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Over $10 million has been raised across sixteen marathons.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Professional streamers can generate livable revenue from viewer subscriptions and donations, as well as platform advertisements and sponsorships from eSports organizations, often earning much more from streaming than from tournament winnings.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The audiences of professional gaming tournaments are primarily livestream viewers in addition to live audiences inside venues.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The International 2017, a *Dota 2* tournament with the largest prize pool in eSport history, was primarily streamed through Twitch, having a peak of over five million concurrent viewers.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Within recent years there has been a large influx in viewership and investment into sports live streaming.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Digital streaming across Prime Video, NFL Digital, Fox Sports Digital, and Verizon Media Mobile properties in 2019 surpassed an average audience of over 1 million – up 43% versus the previous year (729,000).
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Additionally, research and forecasts have shown that consumer spending on traditional pay-TV services fell by 8% to $90.7 billion in 2021 and will decline further to $74.5 billion in 2023.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] It is expected that U.S. household subscription-based services spending will surpass pay TV for the first time in 2024.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Large corporations such as Amazon have looked to expand into sports live streaming.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In 2021, Amazon closed an 11-year, $113 billion deal to stream National Football League (NFL) games on their Amazon Prime Video Streaming Platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Live streaming in sports targets younger viewers with its easy access and subscriptions.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The NFL notably partnered with Nickelodeon for youth-focused livestreams of the 2021 Wild Card Playoff Game and beyond.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] These broadcasts featured Nickelodeon's signature cartoons and commentary from stars Gabrielle Green and Lex Lumpkin.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Despite the growth of live streaming for sports, there are concerns about unauthorised live streaming and piracy of sports content.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In January 2021 alone it was said that humans made 362.7 million visits to sports piracy websites.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] These concerns are exacerbated when studies show over 54% of millennials have watched pirate sports live streams.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] This has created issues over the future sustainability and protection of legally broadcast streams.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In 2023, Netflix began offering live streaming by adding live events such as sports, concerts, comedy specials, and award shows.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] As of 2026, it has broadcast over 200 live events.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Netflix's live streaming was criticized in 2024 when the live stream for the Jake Paul vs.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Mike Tyson fight was marred by glitches and poor quality.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] With livestreaming becoming a financially viable market, particularly for esports, streamers and organizations representing them have looked for metrics to quantify the viewership of streams as to be able to determine pricing for advertisers.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Metrics like maximum number of concurrent viewers, or number of subscribers do not readily account for how long a viewer may stay to watch a stream.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The most common metric is the "average minute audience" (AMA), which is obtained by taking the total minutes watched by all viewers on the stream during the streamed event and for 24 hours afterwards, divided by the number of minutes that were broadcast.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The AMA is comparable to the same metric that the Nielsen ratings for tracking viewership.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] In comparison, the esports Overwatch League had an average of 313,000 average minute audience during regular season games in its 2019 season.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Many instances of serious crimes such as rape and assault, along with suicides, have been streamed live, leaving little to no time for administrators to remove the offending content.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Livestreamed crimes became a trend in the mid-2010s with widely reported incidents such as assaults and suicide streamed through Periscope in 2016 and the kidnapping of a man in Chicago streamed through Facebook Live in 2017.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] A mass shooting in Jacksonville, Florida, resulting in the deaths of two in addition to the shooter, occurred during a *Madden NFL 19* tournament.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Part of the Christchurch mosque shootings was streamed on Facebook Live by the perpetrator for 17 minutes.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Additionally, livestreaming to large audiences carries the risk that viewers may commit crimes both remotely and in person.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Twitch co-founder Justin Kan had been a frequent target of swatting.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] An incident occurred in April 2017 at the Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport when a viewer called in a bomb threat and named streamer Ice Poseidon as the culprit, temporarily shutting down the airport.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] They may also be victim to stalking as with other celebrities; for example, a teenager showed up uninvited to a streamer's house and requested to live with him after having saved up for a one-way transcontinental flight.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Twitch responded by temporarily suspending the harassed streamer.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] Live content streaming has been the topic of numerous papers examining ways to cultivate online communities through live interaction and increase attendance numbers with engaging content.
[src:tencent-cloud/live-streaming] The livestreaming platform Twitch is a common focus among researching trying to transfer its user engagement success to other applications such as improving student participation and learning in massive open online courses (MOOCs).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:tencent-cloud/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Founded in 1998, its subsidiaries globally market various Internet-related services and products, including in entertainment, artificial intelligence, and other technology.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Its twin-skyscraper headquarters, Tencent Seafront Towers (also known as Tencent Binhai Mansion) are based in the Nanshan District of Shenzhen.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In December 2023, architect Büro Ole Scheeren unveiled the latest helix-inspired design of Tencent's new global headquarters in Shenzhen.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Known as Tencent Helix, it will accommodate more than 23,000 employees across nearly 500,000 square meters.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent is the world's largest video game vendor and one of the largest companies by market capitalization in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It is among the largest social media, venture capital, and investment corporations.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Its services include social networks, music, web portals, e-commerce, mobile games, internet services, payment systems, smartphones, and multiplayer online games.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It operates the instant messengers Tencent QQ and WeChat, along with the news site QQ.com.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The company surpassed a market value of US$500 billion in 2018, becoming the first Asian technology company to cross this valuation mark.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It has since then emerged as the most valuable publicly traded company in China, and is the world's tenth most valuable company by market value as of February 2022.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2015, 2018, and 2020, the company was ranked by Boston Consulting Group and *Fast Company* among the 50 most innovative companies worldwide.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent has stakes in over 600 companies, and began focusing on tech start-ups in Asia in 2017.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] TechCrunch characterized Tencent's investment strategy as letting its portfolio startups operate autonomously.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's valuation approached US$1 trillion in January 2021 before it plummeted, but it has since recovered as of November 2025.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent Holdings was ranked 35th on the 2023 *Forbes* Global 2000 list.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent was founded by Pony Ma, Zhang Zhidong, Xu Chenye, Charles Chen and Zeng Liqing in November 1998 as Tencent Inc, in the Cayman Islands.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The name "Tencent" is based on its Chinese name Tengxun (腾讯), which incorporates part of Pony Ma's Chinese name (Ma Huateng; 马化腾) and literally means "galloping fast information".
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Initial funding was provided to it by venture capitalists.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In February 1999, Tencent's messenger product OICQ was released.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Shortly after, Tencent had the client's name changed to QQ; this was said to be due to a lawsuit threat from ICQ and its owner AOL.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The company remained unprofitable for the first three years.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] South African media company Naspers purchased a 46.5% share of Tencent in 2001.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] As of 2023, it owns 26.16% through Prosus, which also owns a stake in Tencent's sister companies, such as OLX, VK, Trip.com Group, Delivery Hero, Bykea, Meesho, Stack Overflow, Udemy, Codecademy, Brainly and PayU.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent Holding Ltd was listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange on 16 June 2004, and it was added as a Hang Seng Index Constituent Stock in 2008.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The company originally derived income solely from advertising and premium users of QQ, who pay monthly fees to receive extras.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] By 2005, charging for use of QQ mobile, its cellular value-added service, and licensing its penguin character, which could be found on snack food and clothing, had also become income generators.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] By 2008, Tencent was seeing profit growth from the sale of virtual goods.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2007, Tencent established its charity foundation, becoming the first Chinese internet company to do so.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] While Tencent's services have included online gaming since 2004, around 2007/2008, it rapidly increased its offerings by licensing games.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] While at least two, *Crossfire* and *Dungeon Fighter Online*, were originally produced by South Korean game developers, Tencent now makes its own games.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 21 January 2011, Tencent launched Weixin (微信), a social media app.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Now branded as WeChat, the app is one of the "super apps", due to its wide range of functions and platforms, and its over 1 billion monthly active users.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 18 February 2011, Tencent acquired a majority of equity interest (92.78%) in Riot Games, developer of League of Legends, for about US$230 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent had already held 22.34% of the equity interest out of a previous investment in 2008.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 16 December 2015, Riot Games sold its remaining equity to Tencent.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent acquired a minority stake in Epic Games, developer of franchises like *Fortnite*, *Unreal*, *Gears of War* and *Infinity Blade*, in June 2012.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] That year, Tencent acquired ZAM Network, parent of Wowhead and other websites, from Brock Pierce.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent in 2013 increased its stake in Kingsoft Network Technology, a subsidiary of Kingsoft Corporation, to 18%.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent previously had a 15.68% stake in the company and raised the stake through a US$46.98 million investment.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent took part in Activision Blizzard splitting from Vivendi as a passive investor in 2013 and now owns less than 4.9% of the shares as of 2017.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 17 September 2013, it was announced that Tencent had invested $448 million for a minority share in Chinese search engine Sogou.com, the subsidiary of Sohu, Inc.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 15 January 2014, Tencent said it would invest HKD 1.5 billion (US$193.45 million) in logistics and warehouse firm China South City Holdings Ltd to develop its e-commerce and logistics business.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 27 February 2014, Tencent purchased a 20% stake in restaurant ratings and group-buying website Dianping for $400 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 10 March 2014, Tencent bought a 15% stake in Chinese e-commerce website JD.com Inc. by paying cash and handing over its e-commerce businesses Paipai, QQ Wanggou and a stake in Yixun to JD.com to build a stronger competitor to Alibaba Group.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 22 May 2014, JD.com got listed on NASDAQ and Tencent expanded its stake in the company to 17.43% on a fully diluted basis by investing an additional US$1,325 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 27 March 2014, it was announced that Tencent had agreed to pay about $500 million for a 28 per cent stake in South Korea's CJ Games.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 27 June 2014, Tencent announced that it had agreed to buy a 19.9 per cent stake in Chinese e-commerce website 58.com (WUBA) Inc. for $736 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 17 April 2015, Tencent announced it bought an additional $400 million worth of shares, rising its stake in the company to about 25%.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 16 October 2014, via its wholly held subsidiary Hongze Lake Investment Ltd, Tencent announced that it had bought a 7% stake in lottery technology firm China LotSynergy Holdings Ltd for HKD 445.5 million (US$57.4 million).
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 23 October 2014, Tencent pitched in $145 million for a 10 per cent stake in Koudai Gouwu, a Chinese mobile shopping portal.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In November 2014, the company announced a deal with HBO which would give it exclusive rights for distribution in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 9 December 2014, Chinese taxi-hailing app Didi Dache announced that it had raised more than $700 million in a funding round led by Tencent and Singaporean state investment firm Temasek Holdings.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 29 December 2014, Tencent launched the website for WeBank (China), China's first online-only bank.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Trials for the service commenced on 18 January 2015.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2014, Tencent sued its major competitor NetEase alleging copyright infringement.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent used its leverage from the suit to convince NetEase to sublicense music rights from Tencent.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The sub-licensing arrangement that resulted then became a model used by other online music platforms in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 30 January 2015, Tencent announced that it had signed a US$700 million deal with the National Basketball Association to stream American basketball games in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Later that year, Chinese automaker BYD became the chief corporate sponsor for Tencent's NBA broadcasts.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 21 June 2016 Tencent announced a deal to acquire 84.3% of Supercell, developer of Clash of Clans, with US$8.6 billion.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In July 2016, Tencent acquired a majority stake in China Music Corporation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Private enterprises in China are required to have an in-firm committee or branch of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) if three or more CCP members are among their employees.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2016, Tencent's CCP branch was recognized as one of the one hundred best such branches in the country.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It provides communications and education platforms including a CCP activity hall, WeChat channel, and an intranet for CCP members where they can take classes related to government and party policies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The Tencent Party Member Activity Center has a dedicated CCP member activity area of more than 6,000 square meters.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] More than 1 million yuan is allocated for CCP activities per year.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2016, Tencent, together with Foxconn and luxury-car dealer Harmony New Energy Auto founded Future Mobility, a car startup (now defunct) that aimed to sell all-electric fully autonomous premium cars.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 28 March 2017, Tesla, Inc. announced Tencent had purchased a 5% stake in Tesla for US$1.78 billion, the automotive control systems of which it subsequently successfully performed penetration-testing until 2019.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In a "direct challenge to Chinese search engine Baidu," in May 2017, Tencent entered news feed and search functions for its WeChat app, which the *Financial Times* reported was used by 770 million people at the time.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In May 2017, Tencent surpassed Wells Fargo to enter the world's top 10 most valuable companies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The site will be used for the education and accommodation of future eSports players, as well as hosting national eSports events and serving as a hub for Tencent's game development.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Aside from Wuhu, another eSports theme park is planned in Chengdu.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2017, Tencent became the 8th most valuable company in BrandZ's Top 100 Most Valuable Global Brands, signalling its growing influence globally as well as the rise of Chinese brands.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Alibaba overtook Tencent as Asia's most valuable company as its stocks surged after the company hosted its 2017 Investor's day.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The company has also developed its own voice assistant Xiaowei, and was in the midst of discussion to acquire Rovio Entertainment, the developer of Angry Birds.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] At the same time, Tencent introduced its mini-programs feature that allows smartphone users to access mobile apps across the globe on WeChat without downloading them.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In July 2017, Tencent bought a 9% share in Frontier Developments, the creator of the *Elite: Dangerous* and *Planet Coaster* franchises; as well as developer for *Rollercoaster Tycoon* 2 & 3.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In August 2017, after Tencent announced the second quarter 2016 financial report, the stock price rose by 6.2% in the Hong Kong stock market, and the market value reached US$429 billion.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent became the second Asian company after Alibaba Group to surpass US$400 billion market cap.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent has also created an alliance to its own AI self-driving program, similar to Baidu's **Apollo Project**, recruiting numerous industry players in the automotive industry.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It is also collaborating with L'Oréal, the world's largest cosmetics company, to explore digital marketing under the Joint Business Partnership (JBP) agreement.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] According to a report by Sina Tech in October 2017, Tencent employed over 7,000 members of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) and that CCP members took a leading role in the development of WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] "With over 7,000 CCP members, accounting for approximately 23% of the total workforce, and more than 60% of whom are core technical personnel, the number of CCP members at Tencent is increasing by nearly a thousand every year.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In November 2017, Tencent revealed that it had purchased a 12% stake in Snap Inc. in the open market, with plans to help establish Snapchat as a gaming platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent remained the largest video game publisher in the world by revenue, and had a market capitalisation of around $475 billion.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In the same month, Tencent announced that WeChat reached 980 million monthly active users, and said to be earmarking billions of dollars to amass a catalogue of user-generated content, in competition with YouTube.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The company became the first Asian company to cross US$500 billion valuation, surpassing Facebook to enter the top 5 list of the world's biggest firms.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In January 2018, Tencent and The Lego Group, the world's largest toy company, teamed up to jointly develop online games and potentially a social network aimed at children.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It also launched its first unmanned shop in Shanghai.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent led a US$5.2 billion investment in Wanda Commercial, together with JD.com, Sunac and Suning Group, to acquire shares in the conglomerate.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Wanda Commercial was renamed Wanda Commercial Management Group.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent bought a 5% to 10% minority stake in Skydance Media.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 23 January 2018, Tencent and Carrefour reached strategic co-operation agreement in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 15 August 2018, Tencent reported a profit decline in the second quarter of 2018, ending a growth streak of more than a decade, as investment gains slid and the government's scrutiny of the gaming business weighed on the company.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Shares of Tencent fell 3% in morning trade in Hong Kong after the rare drop in quarterly profit was reported, extending a slide that has wiped nearly $50 billion in market value from the company in that week.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The sell-off dragged down many other Chinese internet stocks as well.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 6 September 2018, Luckin Coffee signed a strategic cooperation agreement with Tencent.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] China's government designated Tencent as one of its "AI champions" in 2018.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In November 2018, Tencent Charity Foundation donated RMB$1 billion to establish the Xplorer Prize award for outstanding young scientists in areas of basic science and cutting-edge technologies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In October 2019, Tencent began sending out refunds to customers after cancelling the broadcast of NBA games in response to the Houston Rockets general manager Daryl Morey's social media comments in support of protests in Hong Kong.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In May 2020, Tencent purchased the rights to create *System Shock 3* and any further sequels from OtherSide Entertainment.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 29 June 2020, Tencent acquired the video-on-demand service iflix in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In September 2020, Tencent picked Singapore as its hub in Asia, joining rivals ByteDance and Alibaba in the race to reinforce their presence closer to home after complications in India and the United States.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Lazy Audio was acquired from Shenzhen Lanren Online Technology Co for 2.7 billion yuan in January 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Huya Live and DouYu" occurred during 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent later announced too its intention to take DouYu private, in part due to the unsuccessful merger, but also due to lacklustre business performance and disagreements over strategy among company executives.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent is currently the largest stakeholder in DouYu with a 37% stake.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 17 December 2021, Tencent announced it had acquired Slamfire Inc. and its subsidiary Turtle Rock Studios, the developer behind *Left 4 Dead* and *Back 4 Blood*.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In January 2022, reports emerged that Tencent was one of the major tech conglomerates to receive a fine from the SAMR for failing to report their merger and acquisition (M&A) deals in advance.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] According to China's antitrust law, official approval is required before the completion of a M&A deal if the combined annual revenue of all entities involved is at least RMB 10 billion (US$1.57 billion), and at least two entities have at least RMB 400 million (US$62.7 million) in annual revenue.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Of the 13 deals cited in total by the SAMR, each carried a fine of RMB 500,000 (US$78,700) and Tencent received a total fine of RMB 4.5 million (US$710,000) for its involvement in nine deals.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 11 January 2022, it was announced that Tencent was in talks to acquire Xiaomi-backed Black Shark, one of the largest gaming smartphone makers in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The acquisition would have been Tencent's first in a hardware maker and would have overseen Black Shark's transition into a manufacturer of VR headsets to support Tencent's plans for its metaverse business in the future.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Reports initially suggested that Black Shark would be acquired for RMB 2.7 billion (US$420 million), although Tencent walked away from the deal due to regulatory scrutiny of metaverse businesses in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2022, Tencent posted its slowest revenue gain since going public in 2004, partly caused by a 15% decrease in advertising revenue.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The decline was attributed to the pandemic and tighter regulations imposed by the Chinese government.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In September 2022, Tencent acquired a 49.9% stake and 5% voting rights in Guillemot Brothers Limited, Ubisoft's parent company.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 16 September 2022, Tencent took a minority stake in Mordhau studio Triternion.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In November 2022, Tencent announced that it would divest the majority of its US$20.3 billion stake in Meituan through a dividend distribution to shareholders, in part due to China's earlier regulatory crackdown on tech giants.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In January 2023, OpenSecrets reported that Tencent spent over $6.3 million lobbying the U.S. federal government after coming under greater regulatory scrutiny in 2020.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] By January 2023, Tencent had sold its share in Tesla.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Majority owned subsidiary China Literature acquired Tencent Animation and Comics in December 2023.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 22 December 2023, the Chinese government's regulations to curb online gaming cost Tencent $46 Billion in Market Capitalisation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Later, on 27 December 2023, the first of trading after the Chinese government vowed to make improvements to the proposed gaming rules, the firm's stock rose by 5%.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Also in December 2023, Tencent accelerated the pace of buybacks, increasing the pace of daily purchases to about HK$1 billion (with an average of HK$375 million per day) and made a record HK$10 billion share purchase.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In March 2024, the firm uploaded its revenue report for the 4th quarter of the year 2023, recording a surprising 7% rise in the fourth-quarter revenue, slightly missing the expected mark.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In December 2024, Apple decided to have talks with Tencent and TikTok owner ByteDance for integrating their artificial intelligence models into iPhones that are sold in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2025 Tencent released an AI 3D model generator, Hunyuan3D.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 7 January 2025, Tencent was added to a watchlist of companies allegedly working with China's military, along with CATL.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In March 2025, Tencent released Hunyuan T1, a reasoning language model based on the Transformer-Mamba architecture.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] As of 31 December 2025, Tencent own 11.45% of the Universal Music Group through Tencent Mobility Limited and Tencent Music Entertainment Hong Kong Limited, while sharing 39.9% of voting rights.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Launched in February 1999, Tencent QQ is Tencent's first and most notable product, QQ is one of the most popular instant messaging platforms in its home market.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] As of 31 December 2010, there were 647.6 million active Tencent QQ IM user accounts, making Tencent QQ the world's largest online community at the time.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The number of QQ accounts connected simultaneously has, at times, exceeded 100 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] While the IM service itself is free, a fee was being charged for mobile messaging as of 2006.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent also created QQ International, which is an English version of QQ that allows communication with mainland accounts; QQi is available for Windows and macOS.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2005, Tencent launched Qzone, a social networking/blogging service integrated within QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Qzone has become one of the largest social networking services in China, with a user base of 645 million in 2014.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 10 April 2010, Tencent launched Tencent Weibo, a now defunct microblogging service.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] WeChat is a mobile app with functions such as voice- and text messaging, mobile payment, and a friends-only social network called *Moments*.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It is the most popular social mobile application in China and some overseas Chinese communities, for instance, Malaysia.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] As of 2017, WeChat has been unsuccessful in penetrating major international markets outside of China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent publishes video games via its Tencent Games division of Tencent Interactive Entertainment.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It has five internal studio groups under it: TiMi Studio Group, LightSpeed Studios, Aurora Studio Group, Morefun Studio and Next Studio.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Outside of companies subsidiary of its game division, Tencent as a whole has many major and minor investments in domestic and, since the 2010s, foreign game companies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In April 2009, Tencent launched iTQQ, a "smart interactive television service" in a joint effort with TCL.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2015, Tencent launched Tencent Pictures (Chinese: 腾讯影业), a film distributor and a production company that creates and distributes films based on books, comic books, animated series and video games.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In the same year, Tencent launched Tencent Penguin Pictures (Chinese: 腾讯企鹅影视) a production unit focusing on online dramas and minor investments in feature films.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It is under the Online Media Business Unit at Tencent and works closely with Tencent Video.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 21 March 2012, Tencent launched Tencent Comic, and would later become China's largest online animation platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In September 2017, Tencent has announced plans to introduce Chinese online comics to every market around the world, with the first being North America.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It will be working with San Francisco-based digital publisher Tapas Media, a partnership that will see English-language releases of several popular online Chinese titles.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2014, Tencent established exclusive in-China distribution agreements with several large music producers, including Sony, Warner Music Group and YG Entertainment and in 2017 it signed a deal with Universal Music Group to stream its music in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It also entered a partnership with Alibaba Group on music-streaming rights sharing.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The deal aims to protect licensed streaming services offering copyrighted content of the music industry, encouraging more high-quality and original music, as well as developing China's fast-growing streaming market.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Alibaba will gain the rights to stream music from international labels, which already have exclusive deals with Tencent, in return for offering reciprocal rights to its catalogue of Chinese and Japanese music.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The deal between Alibaba and Tencent was an exchange of music licensing that let each company grow its streaming catalog but at a lower cost.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent sub-licensed songs from Universal, Sony, and Warner to Alibaba's Ali Music, while Alibaba shared rights to Chinese and Japanese music from labels like Rock Records, HIM international, B'in Music, and Media Asia.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The deal aimed at reducing fragmentation, support paid subscriptions and promote higher-quality original music in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It also indicated a shift towards broader access.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In December 2017, Tencent's music arm, Tencent Music Entertainment (TME), and Spotify agreed to swap a 10% stake in each other's music businesses, forming an alliance in the music industry which Martin Lau (president of Tencent) described as a "strategic collaboration".
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In October 2019, Tencent Music reached a streaming music distribution agreement with CD Baby and TuneCore to provide independent music artists who distribute music through CD Baby and TuneCore access to the Chinese music market through Tencent's music streaming services QQ Music, KuGou, and Kuwo.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In March 2020, Tencent acquired 10% of Vivendi's stake in Universal Music Group, the world's largest music group.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In addition, it was given the option to buy another 10% with the same conditions.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2020, Tencent bought 1.6% of Warner Music Group's shares after WMG launched its IPO in the same month.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 27 May 2025, Hybe Corporation announced it would sell all of its shares in SM Entertainment to Tencent Music.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2011, Tencent launched Tencent Video, a video streaming website.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It also controls the live-streaming platform Huya Live and has stakes in other major Chinese game live-streaming platform operators, including DouYu, Kuaishou and Bilibili.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In March 2020, Tencent started testing Trovo Live, a live-streaming service for worldwide users.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Since June 2020, it owns the Malaysian Video-on-demand service Iflix.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In late April 2017, Tencent announced it was preparing to launch its virtual reality headset that year.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In September 2005, Tencent launched PaiPai.com (Chinese: 拍拍; pinyin: *pāi pāi*), a C2C auction site.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In addition to PaiPai.com, Tencent launched TenPay, an online payment system similar to PayPal, which supports B2B, B2C, and C2C payments.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] TenPay was one of the first domestic non-bank payment providers to receive a regulatory license following 2010 People's Bank of China regulations that took non-bank third party payment providers out of a legal grey area.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In response to the dominance of the Chinese e-commerce market by Tencent competitor Alibaba Group, Tencent took great effort in its e-commerce platforms.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 10 March 2014, Tencent bought a 15 per cent stake in Chinese e-commerce website JD.com Inc. by paying cash and handing over its e-commerce businesses Paipai.com, QQ Wanggou, and a stake in Yixun to JD.com, as well as purchasing a stake in e-commerce website 58 Tongcheng.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In accordance to this agreement, JD.com would receive exclusive access to Tencent's WeChat and MobileQQ platforms.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In May 2014, JD became the first Chinese e-commerce company to be listed on the NASDAQ exchange, under its ticker 'JD'.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Customers were offered red envelopes with prizes of up to CNY 10,000 and $1,450.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Companies saw this moment as an opportunity to capture AI-curious customers.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Some companies like Alibaba saw such a high demand that they had to add resources in order to end outages on its Qwen app.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 31 December 2015, JD announced that they will stop supporting services on Paipai.com after being unable to deal with issues involving fake goods, and had integrated the Paipai.com team within its other e-commerce platforms.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In a 3-month transitional period, Paipai.com would be fully shut down by 1 April 2016.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] JD relaunched PaiPai.com as PaiPai Second Hand (拍拍二手) to compete alongside 58 Tongcheng's Zhuanzhuan.com, both partially owned by Tencent, against Alibaba's Xianyu in the second-hand e-commerce market.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent was reported in 2017 to be working with China's Central Bank to develop a central payments clearing platform for online payments.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 31 December 2021, it was reported Tencent had bought a stake in the UK digital bank, Monzo.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In March 2006, Tencent launched its search engine Soso.com (搜搜; to search).
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 1 October 2012, it was the 33rd most visited website in the world, 11th most visited in China, as well as the 8th most visited website in South Korea, according to Alexa Internet.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It was also a Chinese partner of Google, using AdWords.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In September 2013, Tencent discontinued Soso.com after it invested in Sogou and replaced Soso.com with Sogou Search as its main search engine.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2008, Tencent released a media player, available for free download, under the name QQ Player.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent also launched Tencent Traveler, a web browser based on Trident.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It became the third most-visited browser in China in 2008.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] QQ Haiwai is Tencent's first venture into international real estate listings and information and is the result of a partnership with Chinese international real estate website Juwai.com.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Haiwai was announced at Tencent's annual regional summit in Beijing on 21 December 2016.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2017, Tencent launched its own credit score system called Tencent Credit, with a process similar to that of Sesame Credit, operated by its competitor, the Alibaba Group, through its subsidiary Ant Financial.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent officially commences operations of its first insurance agency platform, WeSure Internet Insurance Ltd.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] (WeSure), to work with domestic insurance companies such as Ping An Insurance.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In August 2017, Tencent released AI Medical Innovation System (AIMIS) or Miying (觅影 in Chinese), which has two core competencies: AI medical imaging and AI-assisted diagnosis.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The AI Medical Innovation System (AIMIS) is capable of helping doctors screen for various diseases, such as diabetic retinopathy, lung cancer, and esophageal cancer, through its AI-assisted medical image analysis.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Its AI-assisted medical diagnosis engine enables doctors to identify and estimate the risk of over 700 diseases, thereby improving the accuracy and efficiency of diagnoses.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The system is currently undergoing clinical validation in more than 100 major hospitals in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It has already assisted doctors in interpreting over 100 million medical images and has served nearly one million patients.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's data indicates that recognition accuracy reaches 90% for esophageal cancer, 97% for diabetic retinopathy, and 97.2% for colorectal cancer.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Overall, Chinese medical institutions and companies are adopting a proactive approach toward AI.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Nearly 80% of hospitals and medical enterprises plan to implement or have already implemented medical AI applications, and more than 75% of hospitals believe that these applications will become widespread in the future.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Tencent helped source 1.2 million protective masks for American medical staff combating the virus.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 27 March 2020, a co-innovation lab was launched by Tencent who will be in collaborations with Huawei in developing a cloud-based game platform by tapping into Huawei's Kunpeng processor's power to build Tencent's GameMatrix cloud game platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Along with further exploration in the possibilities of artificial intelligence and augmented reality elements in game.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In October 2020, Tencent's AIMIS Image Cloud was introduced.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] AIMIS Image Cloud was designed to help patients manage their medical images and give permission to medical professionals to access their exams and reports.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The AIMIS platform supports full images on the cloud to reduce repeated exams.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It can also connect medical institutions at all levels through cloud based Picture Archiving and Communication Systems (PACS), allowing patients to take examinations in primary medical institutions and obtain expert diagnosis remotely.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Doctors can conduct online consultations through Tencent real-time audio and video facilities when they encounter difficult cases and work collaboratively on images to communicate more efficiently.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] On 26 May 2020, Tencent announced it planned to invest 500 billion yuan (US$70 billion) over the next five years in new digital infrastructure, a major hi-tech initiative that would bolster Beijing's efforts to drive economic recovery in the post-coronavirus era.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent received the Zero Project Award 2023 for innovative ICT solutions for persons with disabilities.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Originating from Tencent's game development, MTGPA (Magic Tencent Game Performance Amelioration) Haptics is transmitting vibro-tactile signals to the user which support orientation and notification.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Typical customers are persons with visual impairments or the elderly.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Connected to the Tencent Map app, MTGPA Haptics guides customers indoors and outdoors through long and short vibrations in case of deviations from the planned route.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent announced its WeCity project in 2019, through which it seeks to develop a smart city solution for digital governance, urban management and decision-making, and industrial interconnections.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2020, Tencent has unveiled plans for an urban development dubbed "Net City", a 21-million-square-foot development, equivalent in size to Monaco, in Shenzhen.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The development will be built on reclaimed land.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It will prioritize pedestrians, green spaces and self-driving vehicles, corporate offices, schools, sports facilities, parks, retail space and apartments, according to the project's architect, NBBJ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] At the end of June 2020, Tencent has increased its direct stake in Nio to 15.1% after acquiring more of the Chinese electric vehicle maker's New York-listed shares recently.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent spent $10 million to buy 1.68 million American Depositary Shares earlier in the month, according to Nio's latest filing with the U.S.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The Shenzhen-based social media and entertainment conglomerate also controls another 16% stake in Nio's ADSs through three of its units.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent was the second-largest Nio shareholder in terms of voting rights after Li Bin, founder of the automaker, who held 13.8% in shares but 47% voting rights, according to a March filing by the company.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] As of 8 July, they bought another amount of shares increasing their stake in Nio to 16.3%.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's largest shareholder is Prosus (majority owned by Naspers), which owns 25.6% of all shares and hence is the controlling shareholder.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] However, Ma Huateng, co-founder of Tencent, still owns a significant stake (8.42%).
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's headquarters is currently the Tencent Binhai Mansion, also known as the Tencent Seafront Towers, which is located in Shenzhen's Nanshan District.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In addition to its headquarters in Shenzhen, Tencent also has offices in Beijing, Shanghai, Chengdu, and Guangzhou.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent has a unitary board consisting of Tencent co-founder, CEO, and chairman Ma Huateng, also known as Pony Ma, non-executive directors Jacobus "Koos" Bekker and Charles Searle of Naspers, and independent non-executive directors Li Dongsheng, Ian Stone, Yang Siushun, Ke Yang, and Zhang Xiulan.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent has at least four Wholly Foreign-Owned Enterprises and nearly twenty subsidiaries.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] A software development unit that has created, among others, Tencent Traveler and later versions of QQ IM, as well as some mobile software.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] This subsidiary is located on the Southern District of Hi-Tech Park, Shenzhen.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] It also holds a number of patents related to instant messaging and massively multiplayer online game gaming.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2023, an entity controlled by the state-owned China Internet Investment Fund took a golden share investment in Shenzhen Yayue Technology.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The stock price of Tencent sank when news of the deal was published.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2007, Tencent invested over RMB100 million in the establishment of the Tencent Research Institute, which became China's first research center dedicated to core Internet technologies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The campuses are located in Beijing, Shanghai, and Shenzhen.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2012, Tencent launched Tencent YouTu Lab, an AI research department that focuses on computer vision, including optical character recognition (OCR), image understanding, and generation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2020, as part of Tencent's efforts to combat the COVID-19 and future pandemic, Tencent established an AI Joint Lab with respiratory disease expert Zhong Nanshan to conduct research on disease screening, prevention, and outbreak warnings.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2023, Tencent debuted its large language model Hunyuan for enterprise use.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2023, Tencent announced its partnership with the Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences (CAAS) to establish a Digital Seed Bank at the Tencent Science and Technology Museum.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] The Chinese government views Tencent as one of its national champion corporations.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] For the occasion of the 19th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party, Tencent released a mobile game titled "Clap for Xi Jinping: An Awesome Speech", in which players have 19 seconds to generate as many claps as possible for the party leader.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In August 2019, it was reported that Tencent collaborated with the propaganda department of the Guangdong Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party and the *People's Daily* to develop "patriotic games".
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In a December 2020 article in *Foreign Policy*, a former senior official of the Central Intelligence Agency stated that the CIA concluded that Tencent received funding from the Ministry of State Security early on in its foundation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] This was said to be a "seed investment" that was provided "when they were trying to build out the Great Firewall and the monitoring technology." Tencent denied this allegation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2021, it was reported that Tencent and Ant Group were working with the People's Bank of China to develop a Central bank digital currency.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In June 2022, Tencent partnered with Shanghai United Media Group to launch a plan to develop domestic and foreign influencers.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent participates in many carbon reduction programs and partnerships.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's Global Carbon Neutral Technology Alliance shares carbon neutrality patents and technologies for free and includes competitors like Alibaba and Microsoft.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent's CarbonX Program is a business accelerator and digital capability program which aims to develop low-carbon technologies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In December 2022, Tencent launched TanLIVE, a climate a co-developed platform which aims to bring together resources for climate change solutions in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] Tencent participates in the Science Based Targets initiative launched by the UN Global Compact, which provides a platform for setting science-based net-zero targets.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p01] In 2022, Tencent established a goal of making the company and its supply chain carbon neutral.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Many of Tencent's software and services share similarities to those of competitors, and to their own.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In 1996, an Israeli company named Mirabilis released one of the first stand alone instant messaging clients named ICQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Three years later, Tencent released a copied version of ICQ, naming it OICQ, which stands for Open ICQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] After losing a lawsuit against AOL, which bought ICQ in 1998, for violating ICQ's intellectual property rights, Tencent released a new version of OICQ in December 2000 and rebranded it QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] With its model of free-to-use and charging for customizing personal avatars, QQ hit 50 million users in its second year, 856 million users and at most 45.3 million synchronous users in 2008.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] During early stages of company development and expansion, Tencent has been widely accused of stealing ideas from its competitors and creating counterfeit copies of their products.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Some of the criticisms aimed at Tencent in this regard are that QQ farm was a direct copy of Happy Farm, QQ dance originated from Audition Online, and that QQ speed featured gameplay highly similar to Crazyracing Kartrider.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In January 2023, Tencent's trailer for their new MMORPG, *Tarisland*, was said to resemble Blizzard's World of Warcraft.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In July 2025, Tencent had been sued by Sony Interactive Entertainment because one of their games *Light of Motiram* heavily resembled *Horizon Zero Dawn* in terms of setting, protagonist, storyline, themes and gameplay.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In general, Tencent does not seek to acquire controlling stakes when it invests in other companies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] It usually deems minority ownership sufficient to build connections and acquire technology.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In a partial effort to rebuild the reputation of Tencent lost from allegations of copying, Tencent adjusted its strategy by aggressively investing in the acquisition of other companies, rather than in the replication of them.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] By 2020, Tencent had invested in over 800 companies across the world.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] During 2012 and 2019, under the direction of President Martin Lau, Tencent has invested from minority stakes to majority stakes in world-wide-famous game companies such as Riot Games, Epic Games, Activision Blizzard, SuperCell, and Bluehole.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] While aggressive acquisitions may benefit Tencent due to factors such as reduction in competition and monopolization, it may not benefit the acquired companies in terms of their growth and innovation.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In 2015, security testing firms AV-Comparatives, AV-TEST and Virus Bulletin jointly decided to remove Tencent from their software whitelists.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] The Tencent products supplied for testing were found to contain optimisations that made the software appear less exploitable when benchmarked but actually provided greater scope for delivering exploits.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Additionally, software settings were detrimental to end-users protection if used.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Qihoo was later also accused of cheating, while Tencent was accused of actively gaming the anti-malware tests.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] The United States Department of Defense added Tencent to its list of entities associated with the Chinese military in January 2025; such companies are either considered to be either controlled by the Chinese military or serve the growth of China's civil-military complex.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] The listing is primarily an advisory, having no direct impact, but nominally is considered a blacklisting.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Tencent representatives said the listing was "clearly a mistake" and will have no impact on their business but plan to appeal the listing.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Since 2018, Tencent has been in litigation with ByteDance.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] ByteDance and its affiliates brought a series of unfair competition lawsuits against Tencent, alleging that Tencent was blocking their content.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] As of at least early 2024, these lawsuits had not reached resolution, largely due to disputes about jurisdiction.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Tencent filed two lawsuits against ByteDance and its affiliates, alleging that they were using WeChat and QQ profiles without authorization and illegally crawling data from public WeChat accounts.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Tencent obtained an injunction barring ByteDance from this practice.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Tencent's WeChat platform has been accused of blocking TikTok videos and the censorship of politically sensitive content.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In April 2018, TikTok sued Tencent and accused it of spreading false and damaging information on its WeChat platform, demanding RMB 1 million in compensation and an apology.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In June 2018, Tencent filed a lawsuit against Toutiao and TikTok in a Beijing court, alleging they had repeatedly defamed Tencent with negative news and damaged its reputation, seeking a nominal sum of RMB 1 million in compensation and a public apology.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In response, Toutiao filed a complaint the following day against Tencent for allegedly unfair competition and asking for RMB 90 million in economic losses.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] However, Tim Sweeney, the CEO and founder of Epic Games, maker of the popular game *Fortnite*, tweeted that his company would never follow suit and punish people for expressing their opinions, even though Tencent is a 40% stakeholder in Epic.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In a statement, Sweeney said it would "never happen on [his] watch", and emphasized that Epic is an American company, implying that it would not compromise an ethos of free speech to curry favor with Chinese authorities in the pursuit of maximum profit.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Later in October 2019, Tencent announced it would stop broadcasting Houston Rockets NBA games in China due to a tweet made by Daryl Morey, general manager of the Rockets, that was supportive of protestors in the 2019–2020 Hong Kong protests.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Although Morey's tweet was hastily deleted, news of it was quickly reported all around the world, and the NBA went on to spend months attempting damage control in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In December 2019, the Chinese government ordered Tencent to improve the firm's user data rules for its apps, which regulators regarded to be in violation of censorship rules.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In January 2021, a proposed class action lawsuit was filed in California against Tencent, alleging user censorship and surveillance via WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In November 2022, Sustainalytics downgraded Tencent to "non-compliant" with the United Nations Global Compact principles due to complicity with censorship.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] On 6 August 2020, President Donald Trump signed two executive orders, one directed at TikTok and one at WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] The TikTok order dictated that within 45 days from its signing (20 September 2020) that it would ban transactions involving the TikTok app with ByteDance, effectively banning the TikTok app in the United States, under threat of penalty.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] TikTok sued Trump over the executive order, which was later revoked under Joe Biden's administration, causing the lawsuit to be dismissed in July 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] The order for WeChat contained the same information but targeting the WeChat app and related transactions for Tencent.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] In the case of ByteDance, the order would be canceled should an American company acquire it, which Microsoft had been openly spoken of, but there are unlikely any immediate buyers for Tencent in the U.S.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] *Los Angeles Times* reporter Sam Dean affirmed from the White House that this does not affect other facets of Tencent's ownerships in American companies such as with its video game companies.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] Department of Justice announced that Tencent had removed two directors from Epic Games' board of directors and relinquished its unilateral right to appoint directors or observers to Epic's board.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-p02] This action followed concerns that interlocking directorates between the Epic and Tencent boards violated U.S. antitrust law under Section 8 of the Clayton Act.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent QQ was first released in China in February 1999 under the name of **OICQ** ("Open ICQ", a reference to the early IM service ICQ).
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] After the threat of a trademark infringement lawsuit by the AOL-owned ICQ, the product's name was changed to QQ (with "Q" and "QQ" used to imply "cute").
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The software inherited existing functions from ICQ, and additional features such as software skins, people's images, and emoticons.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] QQ was first released as a "network paging" real-time communications service.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Other features were later added, such as chatrooms, games, personal avatars (similar to "Meego" in MSN), online storage, and Internet dating services.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The official client runs on Microsoft Windows and a beta public version was launched for Mac OS X version 10.4.9 or newer.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Formerly, two web versions, WebQQ (full version) and WebQQ Mini (Lite version), which made use of Ajax, were available.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Development, support, and availability of WebQQ Mini, however, has since been discontinued.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] On 31 July 2008, Tencent released an official client for Linux, but this has not been made compatible with the Windows version and it is not capable of voice calls.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In response to competition with other instant messengers, such as Windows Live Messenger, Tencent released Tencent Messenger, which is aimed at businesses.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2002, Tencent stopped its free membership registration, requiring all new members to pay a fee.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2003, however, this decision was reversed due to pressure from other instant messaging services such as Windows Live Messenger (WLM) and Sina UC.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent currently offers a premium membership scheme, where premium members enjoy features such as QQ mobile, ringtone downloads, and SMS sending/receiving.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In addition, Tencent offers "Diamond" level memberships.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The QQ Coin is a virtual currency used by QQ users to "purchase" QQ related items for their avatar and blog.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] QQ Coins are obtained either by purchase (one coin for one RMB) or by using the mobile phone service.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Due to the popularity of QQ among young people in China, QQ Coins are accepted by online vendors in exchange for "real" merchandise such as small gifts.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] This has raised concerns of replacing (and thus "inflating") real currency in these transactions.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The People's Bank of China, China's central bank, tried to crack down on QQ Coins due to people using QQ Coins in exchange for real world goods.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] However, this only caused the value of QQ coins to rise as more and more third-party vendors started to accept them.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent claims the QQ Coin is a mere regular commodity, and is, therefore, not a currency.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Qzone is a social networking website based in China which was created by Tencent in 2005.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] It can be set as a public page or a private friend-only page.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Users can upload diaries and share photos.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2009, QQ began to expand its services internationally with its QQ International client for Windows distributed through a dedicated English-language portal.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] QQ International offers non-Mandarin speakers the opportunity to use most of the features of its Chinese counterpart to get in touch with other QQ users via chat, VoIP, and video calls, and it provides a non-Mandarin interface to access Qzone, Tencent's social network.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The client supports English, French, Spanish, German, Korean, Japanese and Traditional Chinese.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] One of the main features of QQ International is the optional and automatic machine translation in all chats.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] An Android version of QQ International was released in September of 2013.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The client's interface is in English, French, Spanish, German, Korean, Japanese and Traditional Chinese.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In addition to text messaging, users can send each other images, videos, and audio media messages.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Moreover, users can share multimedia content with all contacts through the client's Qzone interface.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The live translation feature is available for all incoming messages and supports up to 18 languages.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] QQ International for iPhone and iOS devices was released at the end of 2013, fully equivalent to its Android counterpart.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In India, Tencent has partnered with ibibo to bring services such as chat, mail and game to the developing Indian internet sphere.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In Vietnam, Tencent has struck a deal with VinaGame to bring the QQ Casual Gaming portal as well as the QQ Messenger as an addition to the already thriving Vietnamese gaming communities.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In the United States, Tencent has partnered with AOL to bring QQ Games as a contender in the US social gaming market.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Launched in 2007, QQ Games came bundled with the AIM installer, and competed with AOL's own games.com to provide a gaming experience for the AIM user base.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent launched its web-based QQ formally on 15 September 2009, the latest version of which being 3.0.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Rather than solely a web-based IM, WebQQ 3.0 functions more like its own operating system, with a desktop in which web applications can be added.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2009, Tencent launched Xiaoyou (校友, 'schoolmate'), its first social network website.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In mid-2010, Tencent changed direction and replaced Xiaoyou with Pengyou (朋友, 'friends'), trying to establish a more widespread network, to which extant QQ users could be easily redirected, hence giving Pengyou a major advantage over its competitors.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent's social network Qzone is linked to in the International and native versions of QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Using reverse engineering, open source communities have come to understand the QQ protocol better and have attempted to implement client core libraries compatible with more user-friendly clients, free of advertisements.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Most of these clients are cross-platform, so they are usable on operating systems which the official client does not support.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] However, these implementations had only a subset of functions of the official client and therefore were limited in features.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Furthermore, QQ's parent company, Tencent, has over successive versions modified the QQ protocol to the extent that it can no longer be supported by most, and perhaps any, of the third-party implementations that were successful in the past (some of which are listed below).
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] As of 2009, none of the developers of third-party clients have publicized any plans to restore QQ support.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Tencent has taken advantage of the popularity of the QQ brand and has set up many Q-Gen stores selling QQ branded merchandise such as bags, watches, clothing as well as toy penguins.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Coral QQ, a modification of Tencent QQ, is another add-on for the software, providing free access to some of the services and blocking Tencent's advertisements.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2006, Tencent filed a copyright lawsuit against Chen Shoufu (aka Soft), the author of Coral QQ, after his distribution of a modified Tencent QQ was ruled illegal.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Chen then published his modification as a separate add-on.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] On 16 August 2007, Chen was detained again for allegedly making profits off of his ad-blocking add-on.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The case resulted in a three-year prison sentence for Shoufu.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In 2010, Chinese anti-virus company, Qihoo 360, analyzed the QQ protocol and accused QQ of automatically scanning users' computers and uploading their personal information to QQ's servers without the users' consent.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] In response, Tencent called 360 a malware and denied users of installing 360 access to some of the QQ's services.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The Chinese Ministry of Industry and Information reprimanded both companies for "improper competition" and ordered them to come to an agreement.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Some observers have criticized QQ's compliance in the Chinese government's Internet surveillance and censorship.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] A 2013 report by Reporters Without Borders specifically mentioned QQ as allowing authorities to monitor online conversations for keywords or phrases and track participants by their user number.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] The Chinese version of QQ makes use of embedded advertisements.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Older versions of the client have been branded as malicious adware by some antivirus and anti-spyware vendors.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Both the Chinese and International versions of QQ had been tested in 2013.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] Currently it is identified as malware by DrWeb, Zillya, NANO-Antivirus, and VBA32, who give positive results, most of which identify it as a trojan.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] On March 6, 2015, QQ scored 2 out of 7 points on the Electronic Frontier Foundation's secure messaging scorecard.
[src:tencent-cloud/tencent-qq] It received points for having communications encrypted in transit and for having a recent independent security audit.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Accounts registered with Chinese phone numbers store data in mainland China and are governed by Weixin's terms and privacy policy.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Hong Kong and Macau accounts store data in Hong Kong, while non-Chinese numbers are registered under WeChat, with EU data stored in the Netherlands and other users' data in Singapore.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat personal information may still be accessed from mainland China for support purposes, and interactions between Weixin and WeChat users are subject to both services' policies.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Activities on both versions may be monitored and shared with Chinese authorities on request.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Weixin censors politically sensitive topics and bans content deemed threatening to national security, social order, or state policy.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Account bans can significantly disrupt users' lives in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Tencent also blocks international WeChat accounts for content considered lewd material, violence, scams, rumors, or false ads.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By 2010, Tencent had already attained a massive user base with their desktop messenger app QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Recognizing smart phones were likely to disrupt this status quo, CEO Pony Ma sought to proactively invest in alternatives to their own QQ messenger app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat began as a project at Tencent Guangzhou Research and Project center in October 2010.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The original version of the app was created by Allen Zhang, named "Weixin" (微信) by Pony Ma, and launched in 2011.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The user adoption of WeChat was initially very slow, with users wondering why key features were missing; however, after the release of the Walkie-talkie-like voice messaging feature in May of that year, growth surged.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By 2012, when the number of users reached 100 million, Weixin was re-branded "WeChat" by President Martin Lau for the international market.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] During a period of government support of e-commerce development—for example in the 12th Five-Year Plan (2011–2015)—WeChat also saw new features enabling payments and commerce in 2013, which saw massive adoption after their virtual Red envelope promotion for Chinese New Year 2014.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat had over 889 million monthly active users by 2016, and as of 2019 WeChat's monthly active users had risen to an estimate of one billion.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] As of January 2022, it was reported that WeChat has more than 1.2 billion users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] After the launch of WeChat payment in 2013, its users reached 400 million the next year, 90 percent of whom were in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By comparison, Facebook Messenger and WhatsApp had about one billion monthly active users in 2016 but did not offer most of the other services available on WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For example, in Q2 2017, WeChat's revenues from social media advertising were about US$0.9 billion (RMB6 billion) compared with Facebook's total revenues of US$9.3 billion, 98% of which were from social media advertising.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat's revenues from its value-added services were US$5.5 billion.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By 2018, WeChat had been used by 93.5% of Chinese internet users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In that year, it became the world's largest standalone mobile app in 2018 with over 1 billion monthly active users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In response to a border dispute between India and China, WeChat was banned in India in June 2020 along with several other Chinese apps, including TikTok.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] U.S. president Donald Trump sought to ban U.S.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] "transactions" with WeChat through an executive order but was blocked by a preliminary injunction issued in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California in September 2020.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Joe Biden officially dropped Trump's efforts to ban WeChat in the U.S. in June 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat, has been described as China's "app for everything" and a super-app because of its wide range of functions.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat provides text messaging, hold-to-talk voice messaging, broadcast (one-to-many) messaging, video conferencing, video games, mobile payment, sharing of photographs and videos and location sharing.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It has been described as having "an almost indispensable part of life in China".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Due to its central part of Chinese life, a Chinese person having their WeChat account banned can cause a significant disruption to their life.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat provides a variety of features including text messaging, hold-to-talk voice messaging, broadcast (one-to-many) messaging, video calls and conferencing, video games, photograph and video sharing, as well as location sharing.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat also allows users to exchange contacts with people nearby via Bluetooth, as well as providing various features for contacting people at random if desired (if people are open to it).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It can also integrate with other social networking services such as Facebook and Tencent QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Photographs may also be embellished with filters and captions, and automatic translation service is available and could also translate the conversation during messaging.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat supports different instant messaging methods, including text messages, voice messages, walkie talkie, and stickers.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users can send previously saved or live pictures and videos, profiles of other users, coupons, lucky money packages, or current GPS locations with friends either individually or in a group chat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat also provides a message recall feature to allow users to recall and withdraw information (e.g. images, documents) that are sent within 2 minutes in a conversation.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat also provides a voice-to-text feature that brings convenience when it is not convenient to listen to voice messages, as well as the basic ability to recognize emojis based on different tones of voice.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] A distance sensing feature is implemented in WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It has the ability to activate the receivers' hold-to-talk function when the phone was brought in close proximity to the ear.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] After the receiver was held at a certain distance from the ear, the sensor would then proceed to automatically disable the phone speakers.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This feature eliminates the risk of the user's voice messages being inadvertently broadcast to the general public.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat users can register as a public account (公众号), which enables them to push feeds to subscribers, interact with subscribers, and provide subscribers with services.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users can also create an official account, which fall under service, subscription, or enterprise accounts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Once users as individuals or organizations set up a type of account, they cannot change it to another type.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By the end of 2014, the number of WeChat official accounts had reached 8 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Official accounts of organizations can apply to be verified (cost 300 RMB or about US$45).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Official accounts can be used as a platform for services such as hospital pre-registrations, or credit card service.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] To create an official account, the applicant must register with Chinese authorities, which discourages "foreign companies".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In April 2022, WeChat announced that it will start displaying the location of users in China every time they post on a public account.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Meanwhile, overseas users on public accounts will also display the country based on their IP address.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] "Moments" (朋友圈) is WeChat's brand name for its social feed of friends' updates.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] "Moments" is an interactive platform that allows users to post images, text, and short videos taken by users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It also allows users to share articles and music (associated with QQ Music or other web-based music services).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Friends in the contact list can like the content and leave comments, functioning similarly to a private social network.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2017 WeChat had a policy of a maximum of two advertisements per day per Moments user.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Privacy in WeChat works by groups of friends: only the friends from the user's contact are able to view their Moments' contents and comments.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The friends of the user will only be able to see the likes and comments from other users only if they are in a mutual friend group.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For example, friends from high school are not able to see the comments and likes from friends from a university.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] When users post their moments, they can separate their friends into a few groups, and they can decide whether this Moment can be seen by particular groups of people.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Contents posted can be set to "Private", and then only the user can view it.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Unlike Weibo or Instagram, these are only shared to the user's friends.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Recently, WeChat launched a new foundation that users can choose to top their posts in their own Moments.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] No matter how long the posts can be viewed set by users, the posts topped by them can be seen all the time.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This foundation enable people to mark some important posts that it will be easy to find them.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Besides, users can permanently display some posts while ensuring overall privacy.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users who have provided bank account information may use the app to pay bills, order goods and services, transfer money to other users, and pay in stores if the stores have a Weixin payment option.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Vetted third parties, known as "official accounts", offer these services by developing lightweight "apps within the app".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users can link their Chinese bank accounts, as well as Visa, MasterCard and JCB.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat Pay, officially referred to as Weixin Pay (微信支付) in China, is a digital wallet service incorporated into Weixin, which allows users to perform mobile payments and send money between contacts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Although users receive immediate notification of the transaction, the Weixin Pay system is not an instant payment instrument, because the funds transfer between counterparts is not immediate.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The settlement time depends on the payment method chosen by the customer.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] All Weixin users have their own Weixin Pay accounts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users can acquire a balance by linking their Weixin account to their debit cards, or by receiving money from other users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For non-Chinese users of Weixin Pay, an additional identity verification process of providing a photo of a valid ID is required before certain functions of Weixin Pay become available.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users who link their credit card can only make payments to vendors, and cannot use this to top up WeChat balances.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Weixin Pay can be used for digital payments, as well as payments from participating vendors.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] As of March 2016, Weixin Pay had over 300 million users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Weixin Pay's main competitor in China and the market leader in online payments is Alibaba Group's Alipay.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Alibaba company founder Jack Ma considered Weixin's red envelope feature to be a "Pearl Harbor moment", as it began to erode Alipay's historic dominance in the online payments industry in China, especially in peer-to-peer money transfer.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The success prompted Alibaba to launch its own version of virtual red envelopes in its competing Laiwang service.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Other competitors, Baidu Wallet and Sina Weibo, also launched similar features.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] What was called the 'Red Envelope War', resulted in 16 million red envelopes being sent in 2014 which grew to 1 billion the following year.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Tencent even introduced a new aspect to the red envelope gimmick by allowing users to distribute an allocated sum of money among friends on a first-come, first-served basis, resulting in customers frequently checking the WeChat application.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Alibaba that owns Tmall, Taobao, and Alibaba's e-commerce sites, collaborated with more than 40 sponsors to give away US$123 million to users who participated in its own interactive game during a New Years Gala Show sponsored by China Central Television.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] They also introduced a 'Lucky Card Collection' game that allowed users to collect and exchange cards to become eligible to win cash prizes.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By adding 10 friends to Alipay users could get three cards that went towards the five virtual cards needed to get a share in the US$33 million.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The rivalry continued into 2016 when WeChat sent 8 billion hongbao using the application and blocked WeChat users from sharing Alipay red envelopes with their friends through WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2019 it was reported that Weixin had overtaken Alibaba with 800 million active Weixin mobile payment users versus 520 million for Alibaba's Alipay.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] However Alibaba had a 54 per cent share of the Chinese mobile online payments market in 2017 compared to Weixin's 37 per cent share.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In the same year, Tencent introduced "WeChat Pay HK", a payment service for users in Hong Kong.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Transactions are carried out with the Hong Kong dollar.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2019 it was reported that Chinese users can use WeChat Pay in 25 countries outside China, including, Italy, South Africa and the UK.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat is more of a messaging and social application that offers users a one-time solution for engagement through chats and direct purchases.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It promotes community builiding and more one to one engagement.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Alibaba's in September 2024 announced that Taobao and Tmall would accept WeChat Pay as a form of payment for online purchases.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This allowed people who were used Taobao to pay through WeChat Pay without using the application making a lot easier and faster to make purchases.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For work purposes, companies and business communication, a special version of WeChat called WeCom (formally known as Enterprise WeChat (or Qiye Weixin) and WeChat Work before Nov 2020) was launched in 2016.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The app was meant to help employees separate work from private life.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In addition to the usual chat features, the program let companies and their employees keep track of annual leave days and expenses that need to be reimbursed, employees could ask for time off or clock in to show they were at work.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2017, WeChat launched a feature called "Mini Programs" (小程序).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Business owners can create mini apps in the WeChat system, implemented using proprietary versions of CSS, JavaScript, and templated XML JavaScript with proprietary APIs.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users may install these inside the WeChat app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In January 2018, WeChat announced a record of 580,000 mini programs.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] With one Mini Program, consumers could scan the Quick Response code using their mobile phone at a supermarket counter and pay the bill through the user's WeChat mobile wallet.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat Games have received huge popularity, with its "Jump Jump" game attracting 400 million players in less than 3 days and attaining 100 million daily active users in just two weeks after its launch, as of January 2018.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Ever since WeChat Mini Program's Launch, the daily active user count of WeChat Mini Programs are increasing dramatically.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2017, there were only 160 million daily active users, however, the number reached 450 million in 2021.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] They are a short video platform within WeChat that allows users to create and share short video clips and photos to their own WeChat Channel.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users of Channels can also discover content posted to other Channels by others via the in-built feed.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Each post can include hashtags, a location tag, a short description, and a link to an WeChat official account article.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In September 2021, it was reported that WeChat Channels began allowing users to upload hour-long videos, twice of the duration limit previously imposed on all WeChat Channels videos.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Comparisons are often drawn between WeChat Channels and TikTok (or Douyin) for their similarity in features.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In January 2022, there were reports that WeChat is set to diversify further and place more emphasis on new products and services like WeChat Channels, amid new regulatory restrictions imposed in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By June 2021, WeChat Channels had accumulated over 200 million users, and WeChat Channels have 500 million DAU (Daily Active Users), growing at 79% year-on -year.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] More than 27 million people had used the platform to watch Irish boy band Westlife's online concert in 2021, and 15 million users also viewed the Shenzhou 12 spaceflight launch using the app service.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In September 2021, WeChat introduced a brand-new feature on its platform called Easy Mode.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It was mainly designed for elderly people with higher readability by providing a larger font size, sharper colours, and bigger buttons.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Another feature provided in this update was the ability to listen to text messages.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Easy Mode was released in version 8.0.14 for both iOS and Android.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Guardian Mode is a function in WeChat for protecting users under 14 years old.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It was introduced to promote safety and provide security environment for WeChat users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] After operating the Guardian Mode, the functions of "people nearby", "games", "search" will not be accessible in the interface.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The channels function in WeChat, a video mini program, would only show contents suitable for adolescents.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Additionally, WeChat users who turn on the Guardian Mode are only able to add friends through QR codes and group chats.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Moreover, WeChat users would only be able to view 10 latest Moments posts and would not be able to view the 10 latest Moments posts of non-friend users under the privacy setting of Guardian Mode.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In January 2016, Tencent launched WeChat Out, a VOIP service allowing users to call mobile phones and landlines around the world.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The feature allowed purchasing credit within the app using a credit card.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat Out was originally only available in the United States, India, and Hong Kong, but later coverage was expanded to Thailand, Macau, Laos, and Italy.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In March 2017, Tencent released WeChat Index.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By inserting a search term in the WeChat Index page, users could check the popularity of this term in the past 7, 30, or 90 days.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The data was mined from data in official WeChat accounts and metrics such as social sharing, likes and reads were used in the evaluation.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In May 2017, Tencent started news feed and search functions for its WeChat app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The *Financial Times* reported this was a "direct challenge to Chinese search engine Baidu".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2017, WeChat was reported to be developing an augmented reality (AR) platform as part of its service offering.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Its artificial intelligence team was working on a 3D rendering engine to create a realistic appearance of detailed objects in smartphone-based AR apps.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] They were also developing a simultaneous localization and mapping technology, which would help calculate the position of virtual objects relative to their environment, enabling AR interactions without the need for markers, such as Quick Response codes or special images.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Chinese courts allow the parties to communicate with the courts via WeChat, through which parties can file lawsuits, participate in proceedings, present evidence, and listen to verdicts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] As of December 2019, more than 3 million parties had used WeChat for litigation.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In spring 2020, WeChat users are now able to change their WeChat ID more than once, being allowed to change their username only once per year.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Prior to this, a WeChat ID could not be changed more than once.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 17 June 2020, WeChat released a new add-on called "WeChat Nudge".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The feature was first introduced in MSN Messenger 7.0, in 2005.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Messenger and the feature had interoperability with MSN Messenger's Nudge.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Similar to Messenger and Yahoo, users can access WeChat Nudge by double-clicking on other users' profiles in the chat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This virtually shakes user's profile photo and sends a vibration notification.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Both users must have the latest Wechat update.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] If a user does not have the latest update they will be unable to nudge another user, but can still receive nudges.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] A user can only nudge another user if they have previous conversations.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Newly added friends without previous messages cannot nudge each other.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 16 January 2022, a new version of WeChat has added seven major functions for the iOS 8.0.17, Android 8.0.18 or newer version users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In the function of Personal Information Authority, users can check the number of times personal information has been edited in the past year through the personal information collection list, including head portrait, name, mobile number, gender, region, personalized signature, and address.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 30 March 2022, according to the relevant laws and regulations of China, in order to prevent the risk of publicity stunts in virtual currency transactions, the Wechat public platform standardized the official account and mini program of secondary sales of digital collections.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat Business (微商) is one of the latest mobile social network business model after e-commerce, which utilizes business relationships and friendships to maintain a customer relationship.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Comparing with the traditional E-business like JD.com and Alibaba, WeChat Business has a large range of influence and profits with less input and lower threshold, which attracts lots of people to join in WeChat business.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This is the main profit mode of WeChat Business.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The first one is to launch advertisements and provide services through the WeChat Official Account, which is a B2C mode.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This mode has been used by many hospitals, banks, fashion brands, internet companies and personal blogs because the Official Account can access online payment, location sharing, voice messages, and mini-games.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It is like a 'mini app', so the company has to hire specific staff to manage the account.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] By 2015, there were more than 100 million WeChat Official Accounts on this platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat salesperson in this mode is for promoting products by individuals, which belongs to C2C mode.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In this mode, individual sellers post relevant photos and messages of their agent products on the WeChat Moments or WeChat groups and sell products to their WeChat friends.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Besides, they develop friendships with their customers by sending messages in festivals or write comments under their updates on WeChat moments to increase their trust.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Also, continuing to communicate with the regular customers raises the 'WOF' (word-of-mouth) communications, which influences decision-making.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Some WeChat businessmen already have an online shop in Taobao, but use WeChat to maintain existing customers.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] As more and more people have joined WeChat Business, it has brought many problems.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For example, some sellers have begun to sell counterfeit luxury goods such as bags, clothes and watches.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Some sellers have disguised themselves as international flight attendants or overseas students to post fake stylish photos on WeChat Moments.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] They then claim that they can provide overseas purchasing services but sell counterfeit luxury goods at the same price as the authentic ones.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Other popular products selling on WeChat are facial masks.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The marketing mode is like that of Amway but most goods are unbranded products which come from illegal factories making excess hormones which could have serious effects on customers' health.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] However, it is difficult for customers to defend their rights because a large number of sellers' identities are uncertified.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Additionally, the lack of any supervision mechanism in WeChat business also provides opportunities for criminals to continue this illegal behavior.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In early 2022, WeChat suspended more than a dozen NFT (non-fungible token) public accounts to clean up crypto speculation and scalping.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The crackdown on NFT-related content comes from domestic digital collectibles, which cannot be resold for profit.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In a 2016 campaign, users could upload a paid photo on "Moments" and other users could pay to see the photo and comment on it.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2014, Burberry partnered with WeChat to create its own WeChat apps around its fall 2014 runway show, giving users live streams from the shows.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Another brand, Michael Kors used WeChat to give live updates from their runway show, and later to run a photo contest "Chic Together WeChat campaign".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2016, L'Oréal China cooperated with Papi Jiang to promote their products.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Over one million people watched her first video promoting L'Oreal's beauty brand MG.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2016, WeChat partnered with 60 Italian companies (WeChat had an office in Milan) who were able to sell their products and services on the Chinese market without having to get a license to operate a business in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2017, Andrea Ghizzoni, European director of Tencent, said that 95 percent of global luxury brands used WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2020 Burberry and WeChat collaborated to design a shop in Shenzhen where Burberry has a flagship store, as well as an app allowing shoppers to interact with the shop digitally.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] There are a number of main marketing tactics employed in WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat's mobile phone app is available only to Android, HarmonyOS and iOS.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] BlackBerry, Windows Phone, and Symbian phones were supported before.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] However, as of 22 September 2017, WeChat was no longer working on Windows Phones.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The company ceased the development of the app for Windows Phones before the end of 2017.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Although Web-based OS X and Windows clients exist, this requires the user to have the app installed on a supported mobile phone for authentication, and neither message roaming nor 'Moments' are provided.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Thus, without the app on a supported phone, it is not possible to use the web-based WeChat clients on the computer.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The company also provides WeChat for Web, a web-based client with messaging and file transfer capabilities.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Other functions cannot be used on it, such as the detection of nearby people, or interacting with Moments or Official Accounts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] To use the Web-based client, it is necessary to first scan a QR code using the phone app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This means it is not possible to access the WeChat network if a user does not possess a suitable smartphone with the app installed.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat could be accessed on Windows using BlueStacks until December 2014.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] After that, WeChat blocked Android emulators and accounts that have signed in from emulators may be frozen.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] There have been some reported issues with the Web client.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Specifically when using English, some users have experienced autocorrect, autocomplete, auto-capitalization, and auto-delete behavior as they type messages and even after the message was sent.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] For example, "gonna" was autocorrected to "go", the E's were auto-deleted in "need", "wechat" was auto-capitalized to "Wechat" but not "WeChat", and after the message was sent, "don't" got auto-corrected to "do not".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] However, the auto-corrected word(s) after the message was sent appeared on the phone app as the user had originally typed it ("don't" was seen on the phone app whereas "do not" was seen on the Web client).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users could translate a foreign language during a conversation and the words were posted on Moments.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Weixin, the Chinese version of WeChat, operates from China under Chinese law, which includes strong censorship provisions and interception protocols.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Its parent company is obliged to share data with the Chinese government under the China Internet Security Law and National Intelligence Law.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Weixin can access and expose the text messages, contact books, and location histories of its users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Due to Weixin's popularity, the Chinese government uses Weixin as a data source to conduct mass surveillance in China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Some states and regions such as India, Australia, the United States, and Taiwan fear that the app poses a threat to national or regional security for various reasons.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In June 2013, the Indian Intelligence Bureau flagged WeChat for security concerns.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] India has debated whether or not they should ban WeChat for the possibility that too much personal information and data could be collected from its users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In Taiwan, legislators were concerned that the potential exposure of private communications was a threat to regional security.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2016, Tencent was awarded a score of zero out of 100 in an Amnesty International report ranking technology companies on the way they implement encryption to protect the human rights of their users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The report placed Tencent last out of a total of 11 companies, including Facebook, Apple, and Google, for the lack of privacy protections built into Weixin and QQ.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The report found that Tencent did not make use of end-to-end encryption, which is a system that allows only the communicating users to read the messages.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] It also found that Tencent did not recognize online threats to human rights, did not disclose government requests for data, and did not publish specific data about its use of encryption.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] A September 2017 update to the platform's privacy policy detailed that log data collected by Weixin included search terms, profiles visited, and content that had been viewed within the app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Additionally, metadata related to the communications between Weixin users—including call times, duration, and location information—was also collected.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] To comply with a court order, subpoena, or other legal process.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In response to a request by a government authority, law enforcement agency, or similar body.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In May 2020, Citizen Lab published a study which claimed that WeChat monitors foreign chats to hone its censorship algorithms.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 14 August 2020, Radio Free Asia reported that in 2019, Gao Zhigang, a citizen of Taiyuan city, Shanxi Province, China, used Weixin to forward a video to his friend Geng Guanjun in USA.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Gao was later convicted on the charge of the crime of picking quarrels and provoking trouble, and sentenced to ten-months imprisonment.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The Court documents show that China's network management and propaganda departments directly monitor Weixin users, and the Chinese police used big data facial technology to identify Geng Guanjun as an overseas democracy activist.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In September 2020, Chevron Corporation mandated that its employees delete WeChat from company-issued phones.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Users inside and outside of China also have expressed concern about the privacy issues of the app.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Human rights activist Hu Jia was jailed for three years for sedition.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] He speculated that the officials of the Internal Security Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security listened to his voicemail messages that were directed to his friends, repeating the words displayed within the voice mail messages to Hu.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Chinese authorities have further accused the Weixin app of threatening individual safety.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] China Central Television (CCTV), a state-run broadcaster, featured a piece in which Weixin was described as an app that helped criminals due to its location-reporting features.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] CCTV gave an example of such accusations through reporting the murder of a single woman who, after he attempted to rob her, was murdered by a man she met on Weixin.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The location-reporting feature, according to reports, was the reason for the man knowing the victim's whereabouts.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Authorities within China have linked Weixin to numerous crimes.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The city of Hangzhou, for example, reported over twenty crimes related to Weixin in the span of three months.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2015, Apple published a list of the top 25 most popular apps infected with the XcodeGhost malware, confirming earlier reports that version 6.2.5 of WeChat for iOS was infected with it.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The malware originated in a counterfeit version of Xcode (dubbed "XcodeGhost"), Apple's software development tools, and made its way into the compiled app through a modified framework.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Despite Apple's review process, WeChat and other infected apps were approved and distributed through the App Store.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2015 internet security company Malwarebytes considered this to be the largest security breach in the App Store's history.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In June 2020, the Government of India banned WeChat along with 58 other Chinese apps citing data and privacy issues, in response to a border clash between India and China earlier in the year.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The banned Chinese apps were "stealing and surreptitiously transmitting users’ data in an unauthorized manner to servers which have locations outside India," and was "hostile to national security and defense of India", claimed India's Ministry of Electronics and Information Technology.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 6 May 2017, Russia blocked access to WeChat for failing to give its contact details to the Russian communications watchdog.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The ban was swiftly lifted on 11 May 2017 after Tencent provided "relevant information" for registration to Roskomnadzor.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In March 2023, Russia banned government officials from using messaging apps operated by foreign companies, including WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] President Donald Trump signed an executive order, invoking the International Emergency Economic Powers Act, seeking to ban WeChat in the U.S. in 45 days, due to its connections with the Chinese-owned Tencent.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This was signed alongside a similar executive order targeting TikTok and its Chinese-owned ByteDance.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The Department of Commerce issued orders on 18 September 2020, to enact the ban on WeChat and TikTok by the end of 20 September 2020, citing national security and data privacy concerns.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The measures ban the transferring of funds or processing through WeChat in the U.S. and ban any company from offering hosting, content delivery networks or internet transit to WeChat.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The Justice Department had previously asked Beeler to not block the order to ban the apps saying it would undermine the president's ability to deal with threats to national security.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In her ruling, Beeler said that while the government had established that Chinese government activities raised significant national security concerns, it showed little evidence that the WeChat ban would address those concerns.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] President Joe Biden signed an executive order revoking the ban on WeChat and TikTok.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Instead, he directed the commerce secretary to investigate foreign influence enacted through the apps.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Montana banned the installation of WeChat on government devices since 1 June 2023.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In March 2026, as part of a pressure campaign by U.S. state attorneys general to disrupt drug money laundering on the app, WeChat, but not Weixin, agreed to respond to U.S. law enforcement requests within 48 hours.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The attorneys general of North Carolina, South Carolina, Colorado, Kentucky, New Hampshire and New Jersey subsequently asked the Trump administration to take action against Weixin.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In October 2023, Canada banned WeChat on all government devices.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2022, the Office of the United States Trade Representative (USTR) added WeChat's ecommerce ecosystem to its list of Notorious Markets for Counterfeiting and Piracy.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In January 2025, USTR removed WeChat from its list of notorious markets.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Researchers from Monash University in Melbourne found that less than one in 10 WeChat posts related to the referendum were supportive of the Yes case, most of which were paid advertisements from the official Yes campaign.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The study also found that the vast majority of comments on Voice-related WeChat posts were explicitly supportive of the No case.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Chinese Australians are a very large minority group in Australia, with many using WeChat as a social media platform.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] While the usage of Chinese apps such as WeChat in Australia has long been controversial over its potential links to the Chinese government, but it nevertheless is seen as a major social media platform in Australia, directly competing with Western platforms among Chinese speakers in Australia.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] As voting is compulsory for all Australian citizens over the age of 18, social media advertising is crucial for election campaigns in Australia.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Therefore, the significance of the number of No campaign material, some of which even contained misinformation that most No supporters do not agree with, had the potential to sway the votes of Chinese Australians towards the ultimately successful No case.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat is not the English name for Weixin.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] WeChat is the international version registered with international phone numbers, whereas Weixin is the Mainland China version tied to Mainland China phone numbers.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The two are interconnected, enabling users to communicate directly across geographical boundaries.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Operated by different Tencent subsidiaries, they provide interoperable services including chatting, VOIP calls, Moments, and payment features.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Due to regional legal requirements, Weixin users are subject to the "Weixin Terms," while WeChat users are subject to the "WeChat Terms." During cross-platform interactions, users are mutually bound by the counterpart's terms, and shared information is processed and stored accordingly.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Feature-wise, WeChat exclusively offers WeChat Out.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Conversely, Channels and Weixin Game Center (both in certain regions), Kids Watch, and Voiceprint (excluding the EU/EEA, North America, and the UK) are exclusive to Weixin users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In April 2025 Canadian intelligence officials claimed that the most popular news account on WeChat, Youli-Youmian, had been used for an information operation against the upcoming Canadian elections.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Canadian intelligence linked the operation to China's Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The operation targeted Liberal Leader Mark Carney.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In September 2025, the Government of Nepal banned 26 social media platforms, including WeChat, after the platforms failed to comply with new registration requirements in regard to a new law regulating social media in Nepal.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Following the ban, representatives of WeChat have stated their interest in registering with the law but have yet to file an application for the process.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Starting in 2013, reports arose that Chinese-language searches even outside China were being keyword filtered and then blocked.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] This occurred on incoming traffic to China from foreign countries but also exclusively between foreign parties (the service had already censored its communications within China).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In the international example of blocking, a message was displayed on users' screens: "The message "南方周末" your message contains restricted words.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Please check it again." These are the Chinese characters for a Guangzhou-based paper called *Southern Weekly* (or, alternatively, *Southern Weekend*).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The next day Tencent released a statement addressing the issue saying "A small number of WeChat international users were not able to send certain messages due to a technical glitch this Thursday.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Immediate actions have been taken to rectify it.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] We apologize for any inconvenience it has caused to our users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] We will continue to improve the product features and technological support to provide a better user experience." WeChat eventually built two different platforms to avoid this problem; one for the Chinese mainland (Weixin) and one for the rest of the world (WeChat).
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The problem existed because WeChat's servers were all located in China and thus subjected to its censorship rules.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Following the overwhelming victory of pro-democracy candidates in the 2019 Hong Kong local elections Weixin censored messages related to the election and disabled the accounts of posters in other countries such as U.S. and Canada.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Many of those targeted were of Chinese ancestry.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2020, Weixin started censoring messages concerning the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In December 2020 Weixin blocked a post by Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison during a diplomatic spat between Australia and China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In his Weixin post Morrison had criticized a doctored image posted by a Chinese diplomat and praised the Chinese-Australian community.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In 2016, the Citizen Lab published a report saying that WeChat was using different censorship policies in mainland China and other areas.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The Internal browser in WeChat blocked Chinese accounts from accessing some websites such as gambling, Falun Gong and critical reports on China.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] International users were not blocked except for accessing some gambling and pornography websites.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Later, WeChat was split into Weixin (the Chinese version) and WeChat (the international version) as described in the previous section, with only Weixin being subject to message censoring.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Non-Chinese numbers are registered under WeChat, and WeChat users are subject to a different, less strict terms of service and stricter privacy policy, and their data is stored in the Netherlands for users in the European Union, and in Singapore for other users.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In September 2013, WeChat was blocked in Iran.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] The Iranian authorities cited WeChat Nearby (Friend Radar) and the spread of pornographic content as the reason of censorship.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 4 January 2018, WeChat was unblocked in Iran.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] On 6 July 2021, several WeChat official accounts associated with China's university campuses LGBTQ movement were blocked and then deleted without warning; the official media said they had no knowledge of this.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Some of the accounts, which consisted of a mix of registered student clubs and unofficial grassroots groups had operated for years as safe spaces for China's LGBTQ youth, with tens of thousands of followers.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] State Department expressed concern that the accounts were deleted when they were merely expressing their views, exercising their right to freedom of expression and freedom of speech.
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] Several groups that had their accounts deleted spoke out against the ban with one stating "[W]e hope to use this opportunity to start again with a continued focus on gender and society, and to embrace courage and love".
[src:tencent-cloud/wechat] In August 2023, immediately prior to the Qixi Festival, WeChat launched a mass closure of accounts related to LGBT rights and feminism.
